<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<pageBreakToken pageId="46" pageNumber="47" start="start">Because</pageBreakToken>
Berlese (1908) mentioned &quot;America boreale &quot; as type-locality, Jacot (l.c., p. 241) supposed that the species had been collected at several localities. In the Berlese Collection two slides are present: 72/40 (type) and 208/28; both originate from Washington, which according to Jacot is Washington, D.C.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
The specimens conform to the redescription by Jacot; they closely resemble species of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Steganacarus</taxonomicName>
, but the anal covers are retracted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">1) Probably a lapsus for hystricinum.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
